<IMG SRC="g613688g10j40.jpg" ALT="LOGO">
 </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:18pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL"><I>Treatment of Performance Share Units Granted Prior to the Spin-Off as a result of Spin-Off </I></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">For our NEOs who received grants of LTIP performance share units in 2011 and 2012 for performance cycles extending beyond the Spin-Off, the Compensation Committee
adjusted each outstanding performance share unit post Spin-Off by a conversion ratio of 1.5266. The purpose of the Compensation Committee&#146;s action was to normalize the potential value of each performance share unit because, unlike outstanding
shares of stock, restricted stock or options, LTIP performance share units did not provide holders with any value relating to the Spin-Off of Kraft Foods Group, Inc. Without this adjustment, LTIP participants would have been adversely affected due
solely to the Spin-Off. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:18pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL"><I>2013-2015 LTIP Performance Cycle </I></P> <P STYLE="font-size:12pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>

<TD VALIGN="top" STYLE="BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #bfbfbf"> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:8pt; font-family:ARIAL">Net revenues, excluding the impacts of:</P> <P STYLE="font-size:4pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>

and exits of major product lines under a sales or licensing agreement),</P> <P STYLE="font-size:4pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>

rates).</P></TD>

sale agreements and exits of major product lines under a sales or licensing agreement)</P> <P STYLE="font-size:4pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:8pt; font-family:ARIAL">and
including the impact of</P> <P STYLE="font-size:4pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>

<P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:8pt; font-family:ARIAL">for the Company&#146;s base</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:8pt; font-family:ARIAL">business by eliminating</P>

<P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:8pt; font-family:ARIAL">factors, facilitating</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:8pt; font-family:ARIAL">comparisons to prior</P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:1pt; font-size:8pt; font-family:ARIAL">year(s).</P></TD></TR>
</TABLE> <P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">Except where the Compensation Committee exercises its limited discretion to adjust the final business performance rating under the LTIP,
it does not consider an NEO&#146;s individual contributions as the basis for an award under the LTIP; LTIP awards are based solely on how we performed against performance targets as a company. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">For the 2013-2015 LTIP performance cycle grant, the target objective set for Annualized Relative Total Shareholder Return is the median of the Performance Peer Group
from 2013 to 2015. The Organic Net Revenue Growth and Adjusted Earnings Per Share Growth targets were set relative to historical results of the Performance Peer Group. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">We do not publicly disclose specific LTIP performance targets on a prospective basis. Revealing specific objectives prospectively would provide competitors and other
third parties with insights into our confidential planning process and strategies, thereby potentially harming us competitively. The performance targets are designed to be challenging, and there is a risk that awards will not be made at all or will
be made at less than 100% of the target award level. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">To address unforeseen or unintended consequences, the Compensation Committee retains discretion to adjust the
final LTIP business performance rating for a performance cycle (up or down) by as much as 25 percentage points, allowing the Compensation Committee to factor in a subjective review of quality of financial results, portfolio management, innovation
and talent development. If the Compensation Committee were to exercise its discretion to make a limited adjustment, we would disclose the adjustment. </P> <P STYLE="font-size:12pt; margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt ; font-size:8pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="font-size:12pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:9pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="right"><FONT COLOR="#4c4c4c">MONDEL&#274;Z INTERNATIONAL&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;50 </FONT></P>


<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<h5 align="left"><a href="#toc">Table of Contents</a></h5>

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">Both our Annual Cash Incentive Program and our LTIP awards are based in part on our Organic Net Revenue Growth, but the
Compensation Committee uses a somewhat different benchmark to measure performance for the two separate incentive programs. The Compensation Committee measures Organic Net Revenue Growth performance under our Annual Cash Incentive Program based on
our annual operating targets. In contrast, when setting our Organic Net Revenue Growth targets under our LTIP, the Compensation Committee considers, among other factors, the revenue growth of the companies in our Performance Peer Group. The
Compensation Committee believes that the use of these different targets focuses our executives on critical internal drivers, both in the short- and the long-term, and that the different targets for the two incentive programs, when used together,
closely correlate with shareholder value. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:18pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL"><I>2012-2014 LTIP Performance Cycle </I></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">Any award made for the 2012-2014 performance cycle will be determined based on a weighted average performance rating that includes our performance during the Pre
Spin-Off period and our performance during the Post Spin-Off period. The Compensation Committee also opted to continue using the same measures and weightings of operational goals and relative TSR goals. However, the Compensation Committee adjusted
the targets to reflect our Post Spin-Off attributes. The Compensation Committee used the Pre Spin-Off Performance Peer Group to assess results until the Spin-Off when determining relative TSR performance. The Pre Spin-Off Performance Peer Group
included the following companies: </P> <P STYLE="font-size:12pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>

performance cycle was determined based on a weighted average performance rating that included our performance during the Pre Spin-Off period and our performance during the Post Spin-Off period. The Compensation Committee also opted to continue using
the same measures and weightings of operational goals and relative TSR goals. However, the targets for the Post Spin-Off period have been adjusted to reflect our Post Spin-Off attributes. With regard to determining relative TSR performance, the Pre
Spin-Off Performance Peer Group was used to assess results until the Spin-Off. For the Post Spin-Off period, relative TSR performance was assessed against the Post Spin-Off Performance Peer Group. Following the Spin-Off, the Compensation Committee
determined that the LTIP rating for the Pre Spin-Off period was 183% as detailed in the next section. </P>

<TR>
<TD WIDTH="3%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">(3)</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top">Award value is based on the $34.26 closing stock price on the vest date. </TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="margin-top:18pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL"><I>Requiring Stock Ownership </I></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">To further align the interests of our NEOs with those of our shareholders, and to incent those executives to focus on shareholder interests, the Compensation Committee
requires each executive to acquire and hold a significant amount of our common stock. The following chart summarizes our stock ownership and holding requirements. We believe our stock ownership requirements are comparable to, or are more stringent
than, stock ownership requirements of the majority of our Compensation Survey Group companies. We regularly monitor compliance with these levels. As of March&nbsp;1, 2014, each of our NEOs satisfied the ownership and holding requirements described
below. </P> <P STYLE="font-size:12pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>

 COLOR="#ffffff">Explanation of Key Provision</FONT></B></FONT></P></TD></TR>


<TR STYLE="font-family:ARIAL; font-size:8pt">
<TD VALIGN="top" STYLE="BORDER-LEFT:1px solid #bfbfbf; BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #bfbfbf; padding-left:8pt"><B>Ownership Requirement</B></TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom" STYLE="BORDER-LEFT:1px solid #bfbfbf; BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #bfbfbf">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD VALIGN="top" STYLE="BORDER-RIGHT:1px solid #bfbfbf; BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #bfbfbf; padding-right:8pt">
<P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:2.25em; text-indent:-2.25em; font-size:8pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#4c4c4c">&#149;</FONT>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Eight times salary for our CEO.</P>
<P STYLE="font-size:4pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:1pt; margin-left:2.25em; text-indent:-2.25em; font-size:8pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#4c4c4c">&#149;</FONT>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Four times salary for our other NEOs.</P></TD></TR>
<TR STYLE="font-family:ARIAL; font-size:8pt">
<TD VALIGN="top" STYLE="BORDER-LEFT:1px solid #bfbfbf; BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #bfbfbf; padding-left:8pt"><B>Time to Meet Requirements</B></TD>

requirements. Our CEO may take further action if an executive does not meet the required ownership.</P></TD></TR>
<TR STYLE="font-family:ARIAL; font-size:8pt">
<TD VALIGN="top" STYLE="BORDER-LEFT:1px solid #bfbfbf; BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #bfbfbf; padding-left:8pt"><B>Shares Included As Ownership</B></TD>

ownership, direct purchase plan shares, qualified savings plans, restricted shares and accounts over which the executive has direct or indirect ownership or control.</P> <P STYLE="font-size:4pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>

<TR STYLE="font-family:ARIAL; font-size:8pt">
<TD VALIGN="top" STYLE="BORDER-LEFT:1px solid #bfbfbf; BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #bfbfbf; padding-left:8pt"><B>Holding Requirements</B></TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom" STYLE="BORDER-LEFT:1px solid #bfbfbf; BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #bfbfbf">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD VALIGN="top" STYLE="BORDER-RIGHT:1px solid #bfbfbf; BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #bfbfbf; padding-right:8pt">
<P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:2.25em; text-indent:-2.25em; font-size:8pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#4c4c4c">&#149;</FONT>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Until they meet stock ownership guidelines, our NEOs must
hold 100% of all shares acquired from stock option exercises and restricted stock and performance shares awarded, net of shares withheld for taxes or payment of exercise price.</P> <P STYLE="font-size:4pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:1pt; margin-left:2.25em; text-indent:-2.25em; font-size:8pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#4c4c4c">&#149;</FONT>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Once a NEO meets stock ownership requirements, the NEO
must hold 100% of the shares, net of shares withheld for taxes or payment of exercise price, for at least one year after the stock option exercise or vesting of the restricted stock or performance share award.</P></TD></TR>
</TABLE> <P STYLE="margin-top:18pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL"><B>Voluntary Non-Qualified Deferred Compensation </B></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL"><I>U.S. Deferred Compensation Plan </I></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">In 2013, our NEOs were eligible for the
Mondel&#275;z Global LLC Executive Deferred Compensation Plan (&#147;MEDCP&#148;), a voluntary non-qualified deferred compensation plan. The program is similar to those provided to executive officers at many of the companies within the Compensation
Survey Group and is provided for recruitment purposes. The deferred compensation plan provides an opportunity for executives to defer, on a pre-tax basis, up to 50% of their salary and up to 100% of their award under the Annual Cash Incentive
Program. Executives may invest deferred amounts in eight notional investment options. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:18pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL"><I>U.S. Supplemental Benefits Plan </I></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">We also provide an unfunded non-qualified plan, the Mondel&#275;z Global LLC Supplemental Benefits Plan (&#147;Supplemental Plan&#148;), for eligible U.S. employees. The
Supplemental Plan provides benefits which are not able to be provided under the tax-qualified Mondel&#275;z Global LLC Retirement Plan (&#147;Retirement Plan&#148;) or Mondel&#275;z Global LLC Thrift Plan (&#147;Thrift Plan&#148;) due to an
employee&#146;s compensation exceeding the tax-qualified plan compensation </P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt ; font-size:8pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="font-size:12pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:9pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="right"><FONT COLOR="#4c4c4c">MONDEL&#274;Z INTERNATIONAL&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;53 </FONT></P>

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">
limit under the Code Section&nbsp;401(a)(17), an employee&#146;s election to defer compensation under the MEDCP or under the Supplemental Plan, or a Retirement Plan participant&#146;s benefit
exceeding the limits under Section&nbsp;415 of the Code. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:18pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL"><B>Executive Perquisites </B></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">We provide our NEOs limited perquisites. They include a car allowance, a financial counseling allowance, and, for Ms.&nbsp;Rosenfeld only, personal use of the corporate
aircraft. For security and personal safety reasons, we require Ms.&nbsp;Rosenfeld to use the corporate aircraft for both business and personal travel. Further, having Ms.&nbsp;Rosenfeld travel using the corporate aircraft allows her to be more
productive and efficient when she travels. NEOs are solely responsible for all taxes on all perquisites. We provide the types of perquisites similar to those offered within the Compensation Survey Group and do so at comparable costs. The
Compensation Committee believes that these perquisites are important for retention and recruitment purposes. The footnotes to the Summary Compensation Table under &#147;Executive Compensation Tables&#148; list specific executive officer perquisites.
</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:18pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL"><B>Post-Termination Benefits </B></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">Post-termination compensation consists of
both separation pay and retirement benefits. We do not have employment agreements with any of our NEOs as these individuals, including Ms.&nbsp;Rosenfeld, are &#147;at will&#148; employees. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:18pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL"><I>Change in Control Plan </I></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">We have a Change in Control Plan (the &#147;CIC
Plan&#148;) for senior executive officers. The provisions in the CIC Plan are consistent with similar plans maintained by companies in our Compensation Survey Group, including eligibility, severance benefit levels and treatment of cash and equity
incentive compensation. The separation payments are structured to help assure that key personnel, including our NEOs would be available to assist in the successful transition following a change in control and provide a competitive level of severance
protection if the executive officer is involuntarily terminated without cause or resigns for good reason within two years following a change in control (&#147;double trigger&#148;). Under the CIC Plan, restricted stock and stock options only vest
upon a change in control in the event of a double trigger or if the acquiring entity does not assume the grants. In the event that a payment of a CIC Plan benefit would trigger an excise tax under Code Section&nbsp;4999, the benefit payable under
the CIC Plan will be the greater of the &#147;net after tax benefit&#148; or a benefit that is reduced so that it does not trigger the excise tax. We do not provide any tax gross ups for any excise taxes payable for change in control benefits. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">The severance arrangements and other benefits provided under the CIC Plan (as well as the equity treatment upon certain separations in the event of a change in control)
are described under &#147;Executive Compensation Tables &#150; Potential Payments upon Termination or Change in Control.&#148; </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:18pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL"><I>Non-Change in Control Severance
Agreements </I></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">While we do not have individual severance or employment agreements with any of our NEOs, we would typically provide separation benefits as
consideration for entering into an agreement protecting the Company&#146;s interests in this context. The typical severance payments and other benefits provided to an NEO who is involuntarily terminated other than for cause in a non-change in
control context are described under &#147;Executive Compensation Tables &#150; Potential Payments upon Termination or Change in Control.&#148; </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:18pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL"><I>Retirement
Benefits </I></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">All of our NEOs are eligible for U.S. employee benefit plans. The sponsor of the employee benefits plans covering our NEOs is Mondel&#275;z Global LLC,
a wholly owned subsidiary of Mondel&#275;z International, Inc. and our operating company in the U.S. In the U.S., employees hired after 2008 are not eligible to participate in the Retirement Plan or the defined benefit portion of the Supplemental
Plan. U.S. employees hired after 2008 are eligible to receive an enhanced defined contribution under the Thrift Plan. In addition, accruals under the Retirement Plan will cease after 2019. </P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt ; font-size:8pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="font-size:12pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:9pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="right"><FONT COLOR="#4c4c4c">MONDEL&#274;Z INTERNATIONAL&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;54 </FONT></P>

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">We provided Ms.&nbsp;Rosenfeld with an enhanced pension benefit that credits her pension service for the period of time
(2004-2006) that she was not employed by us. We provided this enhanced pension benefit to Ms.&nbsp;Rosenfeld because, when she rejoined our employment, she forfeited her right to a pension benefit at her previous employer. This benefit was part of a
broader incentive program to help encourage her to return to the Company and become our CEO. The 2013 Pension Benefits Table and the accompanying narrative to the table under &#147;Executive Compensation Tables&#148; provides additional details
about this benefit. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">The Compensation Committee believes that the U.S. tax-qualified Retirement Plan, Thrift Plan and the non-qualified Supplemental Plan are
integral parts of our overall executive compensation program. The supplemental defined contribution program is important because it encourages executive officers, including our NEOs, to save for retirement. The Compensation Committee believes that
our NEOs should be able to defer the same percentage of their compensation, and receive the corresponding notional matching contributions, as all other employees, without regard to the compensation limit established by the Code, for tax-qualified
plan contributions. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:48pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="center"><B><A NAME="toc613688_35"></A>Compensation Paid to our Named Executive Officers in 2013 </B></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL"><B>Overview </B></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">There are no material differences in compensation policies with
respect to each NEO. Our Compensation Committee designed each of our NEOs target compensation levels to be at or near our Compensation Survey Group&#146;s median in 2013. Actual compensation depends on both business and individual performance in any
given year. Below are the specific compensation actions for each of our NEOs in 2013. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:18pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL"><B>Ms.&nbsp;Rosenfeld </B></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL"><I>Base Salary Increase </I></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">Ms.&nbsp;Rosenfeld received a 3.2% salary increase from
$1.55 million to $1.60 million. Ms.&nbsp;Rosenfeld&#146;s salary increase was commensurate with Company guidelines for increases, taking into account her individual performance assessment. Ms.&nbsp;Rosenfeld did not receive a base salary increase in
2012 and will not receive a salary increase in 2014. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:18pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL"><I>Actual Annual Cash Incentive Program Award </I></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">The Compensation Committee determined Ms.&nbsp;Rosenfeld&#146;s annual cash incentive award for 2013 in accordance with the 2013 Annual Cash Incentive Program. Based on
our performance relative to target (business unit rating of 77%), our performance relative to our Performance Peer Group and Ms.&nbsp;Rosenfeld&#146;s individual performance, Ms.&nbsp;Rosenfeld&#146;s actual award was 69% of her 2013 target. The
Compensation Committee considered the following factors in determining Ms.&nbsp;Rosenfeld&#146;s individual performance assessment: </P> <P STYLE="font-size:12pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>

Restricted Stock and LTIP) </I></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">As part of our annual equity grant program, on February&nbsp;20, 2013, the Compensation Committee granted Ms.&nbsp;Rosenfeld 97,600
shares of restricted stock and 487,990 NQSOs (with a combined value on grant date of $4,733,557). This grant reflects her long-term performance and external market positioning. Ms.&nbsp;Rosenfeld&#146;s 2013-2015 LTIP target opportunity is a
percentage of her base salary based on her role. </P>

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL"><I>2011-2013 LTIP </I></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">Applying the
148% rating for the 2011-2013 LTIP performance cycle, the Compensation Committee awarded Ms.&nbsp;Rosenfeld 351,838 shares of Company common stock. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:18pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL"><B>Other NEOs
</B></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">The chart below shows specific 2013 compensation actions for each of the other NEOs. </P> <P STYLE="font-size:12pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>

<P STYLE="margin-top:18pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL"><B>Mr.&nbsp;Brearton </B></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL"><I>Base Salary Increase </I></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">Mr.&nbsp;Brearton received a merit salary increase in April 2013 commensurate with Company guidelines, taking into account his individual performance assessment and
external market positioning. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:18pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL"><I>Actual Annual Cash Incentive Program Award </I></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">Mr.&nbsp;Brearton&#146;s 2013 individual performance rating primarily reflects our overall financial performance relative to target. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:18pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL"><I>Equity Grant (Non-Qualified Stock Options, Restricted Stock and LTIP) </I></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">Mr.&nbsp;Brearton&#146;s equity grant reflects his long-term performance and potential and external market positioning. Mr.&nbsp;Brearton&#146;s 2013-2015 LTIP target
opportunity is a percentage of his base salary based on his role. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:18pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL"><B>Mr.&nbsp;Clouse </B></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL"><I>Base Salary Increase </I></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">Mr.&nbsp;Clouse received a merit salary increase in
April 2013 commensurate with Company guidelines for increases, taking into account his individual performance assessment and external market positioning. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:18pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL"><I>Actual
Annual Cash Incentive Program Award </I></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">Mr.&nbsp;Clouse&#146;s 2013 individual performance rating primarily related to his leadership in delivering strong business
results across the North American region, particularly in the biscuit and candy categories. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:18pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL"><I>Equity Grant (Non-Qualified Stock Options, Restricted Stock and
LTIP) </I></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">Mr.&nbsp;Clouse&#146;s equity grant reflects his long-term performance and potential and external market positioning. Mr.&nbsp;Clouse&#146;s 2013-2015
LTIP target opportunity is a percentage of his base salary based on his role. </P>

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL"><B>Mr.&nbsp;Cofer </B></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL"><I>Base Salary
Increase </I></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">Mr.&nbsp;Cofer received both a merit salary increase in April 2013 and an increase at the time he assumed the role of Executive Vice President and
President Asia Pacific and Eastern Europe, Middle East and Africa. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:18pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL"><I>Actual Annual Cash Incentive Program Award </I></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">Mr.&nbsp;Cofer&#146;s 2013 individual performance rating primarily related to his leadership in delivering solid business results across the European region, despite
tough European Union economic conditions, and early successes in the Asia Pacific region, including strong revenue growth in India. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:18pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL"><I>Equity Grant (Non-Qualified
Stock Options, Deferred Stock and LTIP) </I></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">Mr.&nbsp;Cofer&#146;s equity grant reflects his long-term performance and potential and external market positioning.
Mr.&nbsp;Cofer&#146;s 2013-2015 LTIP target opportunity is a percentage of his base salary based on his role. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:18pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL"><I>International Assignment Payments </I></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">Mr.&nbsp;Cofer, as a U.S. expatriate, received payments in 2013 in conjunction with his international assignments based in Switzerland and Singapore. These payments to
Mr.&nbsp;Cofer were similar to the types of payments generally made to other employees who accept an international assignment with the Company. The payments are designed to facilitate the relocation of employees to positions in other countries by
covering expenses over and above those that employees accepting assignments would have incurred had they remained in their home countries. These payments include housing expenses, cost of living adjustment, education and travel expenses. Similarly,
the tax payments are made pursuant to our International Assignment Policy, which is designed to cover the additional taxes that an employee incurs due solely to the international assignment. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL"><B>Ms.&nbsp;West </B></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL"><I>Base Salary Increase </I></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">Ms.&nbsp;West received a merit salary increase in April 2013 commensurate with Company guidelines for increases. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:18pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL"><I>Actual Annual Cash Incentive Program Award </I></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">Ms.&nbsp;West&#146;s 2013
individual performance rating primarily related to her leadership in delivering strong market share performance with nearly 70% of revenues gaining or holding share and growth in new product revenue. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:18pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL"><I>Equity Grant (Non-Qualified Stock Options, Restricted Stock and LTIP) </I></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">Ms.&nbsp;West&#146;s equity grant reflects her long-term performance and potential and external market positioning. Ms.&nbsp;West&#146;s 2013-2015 LTIP target
opportunity is a percentage of her base salary based on her role. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:18pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="center"><B><A NAME="toc613688_36"></A>Policy on Recoupment of Executive Incentive
Compensation in the </B></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="center"><B>Event of Certain Restatements </B></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">The
Board or an appropriate committee of the Board may determine that, as a result of a restatement of our financial statements, an executive officer received more compensation than the executive officer would have received absent the incorrect
financial statements. The Board or committee, in its discretion, may then take such actions as it deems necessary or appropriate to address the events that gave rise to the restatement and to prevent its recurrence. Such actions may include, to the
extent permitted by applicable law: </P> <P STYLE="font-size:4pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>

<P STYLE="margin-top:18pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="center"><B><A NAME="toc613688_37"></A>Anti-Hedging Policy and Trading Restrictions </B></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">Our current insider trading policy limits the timing and types of transactions in Mondel&#275;z International securities by Section&nbsp;16 officers, including our
NEOs. Among other restrictions, the policy: </P> <P STYLE="font-size:6pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:10pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="6%">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="3%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT COLOR="#4c4c4c">&#149;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top">allows Section&nbsp;16 officers to trade company securities only during window periods (following earnings releases) and only after they have pre-cleared transactions; </TD></TR></TABLE>
<P STYLE="font-size:4pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:10pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="6%">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="3%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT COLOR="#4c4c4c">&#149;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top">prohibits Section&nbsp;16 officers from short-selling company securities or &#147;selling against the box&#148; (failing to deliver sold securities); and </TD></TR></TABLE>
<P STYLE="font-size:4pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:10pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="6%">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="3%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT COLOR="#4c4c4c">&#149;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top">prohibits Section&nbsp;16 officers (and any member of the Section&nbsp;16 officer&#146;s family sharing the same household) from entering into transactions in puts, calls or other derivatives on Mondel&#275;z
International securities on an exchange or in any other organized market, as well as any other derivative or hedging transactions on Mondel&#275;z International securities. </TD></TR></TABLE>
<P STYLE="margin-top:18pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="center"><B><A NAME="toc613688_38"></A>Anti-Pledging Policy </B></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">Our insider
trading policy prohibits our directors, executive officers and certain additional executives from holding Mondel&#275;z International securities in a margin account or pledging Mondel&#275;z International securities as collateral for a loan. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:18pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="center"><B><A NAME="toc613688_39"></A>Policy with Respect to Qualifying Compensation for Tax Deductibility </B></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">Code Section&nbsp;162(m) limits our ability to deduct compensation paid to certain of our NEOs (the covered employees) for tax purposes to $1.0 million annually.
Covered employees include our principal executive officer and our next three highest paid executive officers, other than our principal financial officer. This limitation does not apply to performance-based compensation, provided certain conditions
are satisfied. For 2013, annual cash incentive program awards, stock options and restricted stock granted and performance shares awarded to covered employees were subject to, and made in accordance with, performance-based compensation arrangements
previously implemented that were intended to qualify as tax-deductible. However, the application of Section&nbsp;162(m) is complex and may change with time (with potentially retroactive effect) and thus there can be no guarantee that all of these
elements will actually qualify as performance-based compensation under Section&nbsp;162(m). </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">We intend to qualify time-vested restricted stock grants made to our
covered employees using the performance-based compensation exemption. In February 2010, the Compensation Committee approved a formula to determine the maximum number of restricted shares granted to the covered employees. Grants were entirely
contingent upon the Company achieving adjusted net earnings threshold during a one-year performance period prior to the stock grant. Under the formula, the value of the maximum number of restricted shares that could be granted under our 2013 annual
restricted stock program was equal to 1.50% of our adjusted net earnings in 2012. We defined adjusted net earnings as net earnings before extraordinary items, discontinued operations and the cumulative effect of accounting changes and excluding
certain other items designated by the Compensation Committee. In addition, our Amended and Restated 2005 Performance Incentive Plan limits individual annual restricted stock grants to 1.0&nbsp;million shares. In February 2013, using the adjusted net
earnings formula, the Compensation Committee determined the grant value pool for the 2013 restricted stock grants. The maximum grant available for our CEO was equal to one-third of the pool. The remaining two-thirds of the pool was available for
allocation among the remaining covered employees, subject in each instance to the maximum individual grant amount under our Amended and Restated 2005 Performance Incentive Plan. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">The Compensation Committee has retained the discretion to authorize payments that may not be tax-deductible, if it believes that such payments are in the best interest
of shareholders. For example, the Compensation Committee decided, based on benchmarking salaries of other chief executive officers in the Compensation Survey Group, to pay Ms.&nbsp;Rosenfeld an annual base salary in excess of $1.0 million.
Therefore, a portion of her salary was not tax-deductible in 2013. In addition a portion of certain of the other covered employees&#146; income exceeded the $1.0 million tax deductibility limit in 2013 because of other elements of their annual
compensation. </P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt ; font-size:8pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="font-size:12pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>

<TR>
<TD WIDTH="3%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">(1)</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top">The stock grants column includes restricted stock or deferred stock units and performance shares. The amounts shown in this column represent the full grant date fair value of the stock grants made in each year as
computed in accordance with FASB ASC Topic 718. For performance shares, the amounts are based on the probable outcome of the performance conditions as of the grant date. Assumptions used in the calculation of these amounts are included in Note 11 to
the consolidated financial statements contained in our Annual Report on Form&nbsp;10-K for the fiscal year ended December&nbsp;31, 2013 (the &#147;Form 10-K&#148;). Below is a breakout of the 2013 &#150; 2015, 2012 &#150; 2014 and 2011 &#150; 2013
performance share grant date fair values assuming target performance and maximum performance (in the case of maximum, based on the maximum number of shares multiplied by the stock price on the grant date). Also shown in the table below (for 2012
only) is the performance-contingent restricted stock units grant date fair value assuming performance conditions are satisfied, and the maximum value (in the case of the maximum value, the value shown is based on the maximum number of units
multiplied by the stock price on the grant date). </TD></TR></TABLE>

<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:8pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="3%">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="4%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">(a)</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top">For reasons of security and personal safety, we require Ms.&nbsp;Rosenfeld to use our aircraft for all travel. The incremental cost of personal use of our aircraft, as reflected in the table, includes the cost of
trip-related crew hotels and meals, in-flight food and beverages, landing and ground handling fees, hourly maintenance contract costs, hangar or aircraft parking costs, fuel costs based on the average annual cost of fuel per hour flown, and other
smaller variable costs. Fixed costs that would be incurred in any event to operate our aircraft (for example, aircraft purchase costs, maintenance not related to personal trips and flight crew salaries) are not included in the incremental cost of
Ms.&nbsp;Rosenfeld&#146;s use of our aircraft. Ms.&nbsp;Rosenfeld is responsible for taxes in connection with her personal use of our aircraft and is not reimbursed for such taxes. </TD></TR></TABLE>
<P STYLE="font-size:6pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:8pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="3%">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="4%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">(b)</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top">Mr.&nbsp;Cofer, as a U.S. expatriate, received payments in 2013 in conjunction with his international assignments based in Switzerland and Singapore.&nbsp;These payments to Mr.&nbsp;Cofer were similar to the types of
payments generally made to other employees who accept an international assignment with the Company. The payments are designed to facilitate the relocation of employees to positions in other countries by covering expenses over and above those that
employees accepting assignments would have incurred had they remained in their home countries.&nbsp;These payments include housing expenses, cost of living adjustment, schooling and travel expenses.&nbsp;Similarly, the tax payments are made pursuant
to our International Assignment Policy, which is designed to cover the additional taxes that an employee incurs due solely to the international assignment. The tax equalization amount is negative due to the timing of host country tax expenses
incurred. </TD></TR></TABLE>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt ; font-size:8pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="font-size:12pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>

<TR>
<TD WIDTH="3%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">(1)</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top">The target amounts represent the potential cash payout if both business and individual performance are at target levels under our 2013 Annual Cash Incentive Program (&#147;AIP&#148;). Actual amounts under the AIP were
awarded in March 2014 and are disclosed in the 2013 Summary Compensation Table. The maximum amounts are equal to 250% of target. </TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:4pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>

<TR>
<TD WIDTH="3%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">(2)</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top">The performance shares are granted under our 2013 &#150; 2015 LTIP. The target number of shares shown in the table reflects the number of shares of our common stock that will be earned if each of the performance metrics
are at target levels. Actual shares awarded under the 2013 &#150; 2015 LTIP, if any, are scheduled to be paid in March 2016. Dividend equivalents accrue during the performance period on shares earned during the performance cycle and will be paid out
in cash as of the award date for the performance cycle &#150; which generally occurs in the first quarter following the end of the performance cycle provided shares are awarded. The maximum amounts are equal to 200% of target. </TD></TR></TABLE>
<P STYLE="font-size:4pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>

<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top">Dividends are paid on the unvested restricted stock at the same rate as for Mondel&#275;z International shareholders. </TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:4pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>

<TD WIDTH="3%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">(4)</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top">The exercise price of the stock option grants represents the fair market value (average of high and low stock prices) of our common stock on the grant date. For the stock options granted on February&nbsp;20, 2013, the
exercise price is greater than the closing stock price ($27.03) on that date. </TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:4pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>

Company&#146;s closing price maintains an average at or above the specific threshold for a minimum period of ten consecutive trading days. 25% will vest after the stock price appreciates 20% from the FMV on the grant date ($31.12), 37.5% will vest
after the stock price appreciates 30% from the FMV on the grant date ($33.72), and 37.5% will vest after the stock price appreciates 40% from the FMV on the grant date ($36.31). On April 29 and November 26, 2013, respectively, the first and second
share price thresholds were met after the stock closing price averaged $31.195 and $33.793 for ten consecutive trading days, respectively. Generally, the performance-contingent restricted stock units will not vest prior to the three-year anniversary
of the grant date.</TD></TR>

<P STYLE="margin-top:18pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="center"><B><A NAME="toc613688_46"></A>Retirement Benefit Plan Descriptions </B></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">Both the qualified and supplemental retirement plans are generally offered to executive officers, including the NEOs, and vary by country. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:18pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL"><B>Mondel&#275;z Global LLC Retirement Plan </B></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">Beginning January&nbsp;1, 2009,
this program is not offered to newly hired U.S. employees. However, all eligible full-time and part-time U.S. employees hired before January&nbsp;1, 2009, including our NEOs, are covered automatically in our funded non-contributory, tax-qualified
defined benefit plan. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">Benefits under this plan are payable upon retirement in the form of an annuity or a lump sum (if the employee was hired before 2004). Normal
retirement under this plan is defined as age 65 with five years of vesting service, at which point participants are eligible to receive an unreduced benefit. Vested participants may elect to receive benefits before age 65, but the amount is reduced
as benefits are paid over a longer period of time. Participants must have at least five years of service to become vested. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">The formula used to calculate a benefit
is equal to the following: </P> <P STYLE="font-size:4pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:10pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="6%">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="3%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT COLOR="#4c4c4c">&#149;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top">1.3% of final average pay up to the Social Security covered compensation amount multiplied by years of service up to 30; plus </TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:4pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:10pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="6%">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="3%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT COLOR="#4c4c4c">&#149;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top">1.675% of final average pay in excess of the Social Security covered compensation amount, multiplied by years of service up to 30; plus </TD></TR></TABLE>
<P STYLE="font-size:4pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:10pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="6%">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="3%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT COLOR="#4c4c4c">&#149;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top">0.5% of final average pay multiplied by years of service in excess of 30. Final average pay is defined as the greater of (a)&nbsp;the average of an executive officer&#146;s salary plus annual bonus during the last 60
consecutive months of service before separation and (b)&nbsp;the five highest consecutive calendar years of salary plus annual bonus out of the last ten years prior to separation. Social Security covered compensation is an amount equal to the
average of the Social Security taxable wage bases for the 35-year period that ends in the year the participant reaches age 65. (If you were born between 1938 and 1954, the 35-year average ends in the year you reach age 66. If you were born after
1954, the 35-year average ends in the year you reach age 67). The Internal Revenue Service has established certain limits on how much employees may receive from this plan. </TD></TR></TABLE>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">As of December&nbsp;31, 2013, Ms.&nbsp;Rosenfeld is eligible to retire under the Mondel&#275;z Global LLC Retirement Plan. Employees hired before January&nbsp;1, 2004,
with at least ten years of service, are eligible to retire under this plan at age 55. The benefits payable to employees eligible to retire before age 62 are reduced by 3% each year (maximum 20%) between age 62 and the year that the employee retires.
</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:18pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL"><B>Mondel&#275;z Global LLC Supplemental Benefits Plan I </B></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">The Code limits
the amount employees may receive from the tax-qualified pension plan. Therefore, we offer a Supplemental Defined Benefit Pension Plan and several NEOs participate in this plan. Beginning January&nbsp;1, 2009, this program is not offered to newly
hired U.S. employees. However, all eligible full-time and part-time U.S. employees hired before January&nbsp;1, 2009, including our NEOs, may participate in this unfunded plan that provides for the difference between what would have been payable
based upon the pension plan formula stated above absent the applicable Code limits and the amount actually payable from the Mondel&#275;z Global LLC Retirement Plan. Additionally, any eligible base salary and annual cash incentive deferrals made
under the voluntary non-qualified deferred compensation plan are considered non-qualified earnings and are subsequently paid out under this plan regardless of whether or not the executive exceeds the applicable Code limits. Ms.&nbsp;Rosenfeld is
eligible to retire </P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt ; font-size:8pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="font-size:12pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:9pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="right"><FONT COLOR="#4c4c4c">MONDEL&#274;Z INTERNATIONAL&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;67 </FONT></P>


<p Style='page-break-before:always'>

<h5 align="left"><a href="#toc">Table of Contents</a></h5>

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">
under the Mondel&#275;z Global LLC Supplemental Benefits Plan I. Employees hired before January&nbsp;1, 2004, with at least ten years of service, are eligible to retire under this plan at age 55.
The benefits payable to employees eligible to retire before age 62 are reduced by 3% each year (maximum 20%) between age 62 and the year that the employee retires. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:18pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL"><B>Mondel&#275;z Global LLC Supplemental Benefits Plan II &#150; Ms.&nbsp;Rosenfeld </B></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">Ms.&nbsp;Rosenfeld&#146;s employment offer letter provided her with credited service during the period she was not working for the Company between 2004 and 2006. This
enhanced pension benefit was part of a broader incentive program designed to compensate Ms.&nbsp;Rosenfeld for the forfeiture of benefits at her prior employer, as well as to encourage her to return to the Company. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">As of December&nbsp;31, 2013, Ms.&nbsp;Rosenfeld is eligible to retire under the Mondel&#275;z Global LLC Supplemental Benefits Plan II. The benefits payable to
Ms.&nbsp;Rosenfeld before age 62 are reduced by 3% each year (maximum 20%) between age 62 and the year that she retires. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:18pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL"><B>Mondelez Canada Inc. Retirement Plan
for Canadian Salaried Employees &#150; Mr.&nbsp;Brearton </B></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">Beginning January&nbsp;1, 1991, this plan is not offered to newly hired Canadian employees. However,
all eligible full-time and part-time General Foods Canadian salaried employees hired before January&nbsp;1, 1991 are eligible to participate in our funded non-contributory, tax-qualified defined pension plan. All other Canadian employees hired after
December&nbsp;31, 1990 are eligible to participate in the Mondelez Canada Inc. contributory defined benefit pension plan. Benefits under this plan are payable upon retirement in the form of a monthly pension payment. Normal retirement under this
plan is defined as age 65, at which point participants are eligible to receive an unreduced benefit. Participants may elect to receive benefits before age 65 but the amount is reduced as benefits are paid over a longer period of time. Participants
under age 55 must have at least two years of service to become vested. Participants over age 55 are immediately vested. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">The formula used to calculate a benefit is
equal to the following: </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:4pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL"><I>Post December&nbsp;31, 1986</I> &#150; 1.25% of final average earnings (five years) less 1.4285% of the Canada Pension Plan benefit,
multiplied by credited service in the plan (maximum 35 years) </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:18pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL"><I>Pre January&nbsp;1, 1987 &#150; Better of: </I></P>
<P STYLE="font-size:4pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:10pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="6%">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="3%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT COLOR="#4c4c4c">&#149;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top">1.25% of final average earnings (five years) less 1.4285% of the Canada Pension Plan benefit, multiplied by credited service in the plan (maximum 30 years). </TD></TR></TABLE>
<P STYLE="font-size:4pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:10pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="6%">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="4%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">&nbsp;&nbsp;</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top">OR </TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:4pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:10pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="6%">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="3%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT COLOR="#4c4c4c">&#149;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top">1.00% of final average earnings (five years) multiplied by credited service in the plan (maximum 30 years). </TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="margin-top:4pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">Employees
hired before January&nbsp;1, 1991 are eligible to retire under this plan at age 55. The benefits payable to employees eligible to retire before age 65 are reduced by 4% for each year (maximum 20%) between age 55 and age 60. The benefits are
unreduced after age 60. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:18pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL"><B>Mondelez Canada Inc. Supplemental Benefits Plan &#150; Mr.&nbsp;Brearton </B></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">The Canadian Government limits the amount employees may receive from the tax-qualified pension plan. Therefore, we offer a Supplemental Defined Benefit Pension. All
eligible full-time and part-time salaried employees may participate in this unfunded plan that provides for the difference between what would have been payable based upon the pension plan formula stated above and the amount actually payable from the
Mondelez Canada Inc. Retirement Plan for Canadian Salaried Employees. Eligible employees may retire under this plan at age 55. The benefits payable to employees eligible to retire before age 65 are reduced by 4% each year (maximum 20%) between age
55 and age 60. The benefits are unreduced after age 60. </P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt ; font-size:8pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="font-size:12pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:9pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="right"><FONT COLOR="#4c4c4c">MONDEL&#274;Z INTERNATIONAL&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;68 </FONT></P>

<TD WIDTH="3%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">(4)</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top">The aggregate balance includes amounts that were reported as compensation for our NEOs in prior years. Amounts reported attributable to base salary, AIP awards or all other compensation that were reported in the Summary
Compensation Table of previously filed proxy statements for the participating NEOs are as follows: Ms.&nbsp;Rosenfeld &#150; $4,175,528; Mr.&nbsp;Brearton &#150; $786,582; Mr.&nbsp;Clouse &#150; $0; Mr.&nbsp;Cofer &#150; $91,747 and Ms.&nbsp;West
&#150; $244,896. </TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="margin-top:18pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL"><B>U.S. Supplemental Defined Contribution Plan </B></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">Because the Internal Revenue Code limits the amount that may be contributed to the tax-qualified defined contribution plan on behalf of an employee, we offer a
Supplemental Defined Contribution Plan. This is an unfunded plan that allows eligible employees to defer a portion of their annual compensation (base salary and annual cash incentive awards) and receive corresponding matching amounts to the extent
that their contributions to the tax-qualified defined contribution plan (and the corresponding matching contributions) are limited by Code Section&nbsp;401(a)(17) or 415. Executives must defer receipt of the payments until retirement. Executive
contributions and employer matching amounts earn the same rate of return as the Interest Income Fund, which is a market rate fund available to employees in the tax-qualified defined contribution plan. The rate of return under this investment fund in
2013 was 2.24%. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:18pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL"><B>U.S. Executive Deferred Compensation Plan </B></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">The
Mondel&#275;z Global LLC Executive Deferred Compensation Plan is a non-qualified plan that allows our NEOs to defer, on a pre-tax basis, up to 50% of salary and up to 100% of their annual cash incentive award. The investment choices are similar to
those offered to eligible employees in our U.S. 401(k) plan. Participants may elect to defer their compensation until they separate from service for purposes of Code Section&nbsp;409A. They may also elect to receive distributions of their accounts
while still employed with Mondel&#275;z International, but the plan requires a minimum deferral period of two years. Distributions may be made in a lump sum or in annual installments of between two and ten years. </P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt ; font-size:8pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="font-size:12pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:9pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="right"><FONT COLOR="#4c4c4c">MONDEL&#274;Z INTERNATIONAL&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;69 </FONT></P>


<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<h5 align="left"><a href="#toc">Table of Contents</a></h5>

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="center"><B><A NAME="toc613688_48"></A>Potential Payments Upon Termination or Change-in-Control </B></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">The tables and narrative below describe the potential payments to each NEO upon termination. Other than the types of compensation and benefits described in the tables
below or as would be received by all other salaried employees or accrued balances pursuant to our retirement plans, no other payments are earned by, or would be awarded to, the NEO. In accordance with SEC rules, all information described in this
section is presented as if a triggering event occurred on December&nbsp;31, 2013. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:18pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL"><B>Involuntary Termination Without Cause (Non-Change-in-Control Event) </B></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">We do not have existing employment or separation agreements with our NEOs which would dictate terms on the NEO&#146;s departure from the Company. However, in the event
an NEO is involuntarily terminated without cause outside of a change in control event, we expect that in most cases our Compensation Committee would offer separation benefits as consideration for protections we would likely seek &#150; such as a
release of claims and having the departing NEO enter into non-compete, confidentiality and non-solicitation agreements. Providing separation benefits to executives who are involuntarily terminated without cause is also valuable in attracting and
retaining leaders. Further, for our U.S. salaried employees we maintain a severance plan which provides severance pay of up to 12 months based on service where the employee&#146;s job is eliminated. We would expect to treat our NEOs at least
comparably to other U.S. salaried employees who leave the Company without cause due to our actions. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">The chart below reflects the typical separation benefits that
may be offered an NEO who is involuntarily terminated without cause. Of course, ultimately the specific terms and conditions would be determined by our Compensation Committee based on the particular facts in a specific case. </P>
<P STYLE="font-size:12pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE CELLSPACING="0" CELLPADDING="0" WIDTH="100%" BORDER="0" STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:8pt" ALIGN="center">

welfare benefits coverage also continues. If no salary continuation, no continuation of benefits.</P></TD></TR>

<P STYLE="margin-top:18pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL"><B>Change in Control Arrangements </B></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">The key elements of the CIC Plan, including
amendments, are provided in the table below. </P> <P STYLE="font-size:12pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE CELLSPACING="0" CELLPADDING="0" WIDTH="100%" BORDER="0" STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:8pt">


<TR>
<TD WIDTH="18%"></TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom" WIDTH="1%"></TD>
<TD WIDTH="80%"></TD></TR>
<TR BGCOLOR="#4c4c4c" STYLE="font-family:ARIAL; font-size:8pt">
<TD VALIGN="bottom" ALIGN="center" STYLE="BORDER-LEFT:1px solid #bfbfbf; padding-left:8pt;border-bottom:1.00pt solid #000000"> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:1pt; font-size:8pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="center"><FONT COLOR="#ffffff"><B><FONT
 COLOR="#ffffff">Plan Element</FONT></B></FONT></P></TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom" STYLE="BORDER-LEFT:1px solid #bfbfbf">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom" ALIGN="center" STYLE="BORDER-RIGHT:1px solid #bfbfbf; padding-right:8pt;border-bottom:1.00pt solid #000000"> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:1pt; font-size:8pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="center"><FONT COLOR="#ffffff"><B><FONT
 COLOR="#ffffff">Description</FONT></B></FONT></P></TD></TR>


<TR STYLE="font-family:ARIAL; font-size:8pt">
<TD VALIGN="top" STYLE="BORDER-LEFT:1px solid #bfbfbf; BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #bfbfbf; padding-left:8pt">Definition&nbsp;of&nbsp;Change in&nbsp;Control (&#147;CIC&#148;)</TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom" STYLE="BORDER-LEFT:1px solid #bfbfbf; BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #bfbfbf">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD VALIGN="top" STYLE="BORDER-RIGHT:1px solid #bfbfbf; BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #bfbfbf; padding-right:8pt"> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:8pt; font-family:ARIAL">Subject to certain exceptions, the occurrence of one of the
conditions below:</P> <P STYLE="font-size:4pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:2.25em; text-indent:-2.25em; font-size:8pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#4c4c4c">&#149;</FONT>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Acquisition of 20% or more of our outstanding voting
securities;</P> <P STYLE="font-size:4pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:2.25em; text-indent:-2.25em; font-size:8pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#4c4c4c">&#149;</FONT>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Changes to Board membership during any consecutive
24-month period that results in less than 50% of the current Board members elected to the Board;</P> <P STYLE="font-size:4pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:2.25em; text-indent:-2.25em; font-size:8pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#4c4c4c">&#149;</FONT>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Our merger or consolidation with another company, and</P>
<P STYLE="font-size:4pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:4.25em; text-indent:-2.00em; font-size:8pt; font-family:ARIAL">a)&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;we are not the surviving company;
or</P> <P STYLE="font-size:4pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:4.25em; text-indent:-2.00em; font-size:8pt; font-family:ARIAL">b)&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;the other entity owns 50%
or more of our outstanding voting securities; or</P> <P STYLE="font-size:4pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:1pt; margin-left:2.25em; text-indent:-2.25em; font-size:8pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT
 COLOR="#4c4c4c">&#149;</FONT>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Complete liquidation of Mondel&#275;z International or the sale of all or substantially all of our assets.</P></TD></TR>
<TR STYLE="font-family:ARIAL; font-size:8pt">
<TD VALIGN="top" STYLE="BORDER-LEFT:1px solid #bfbfbf; BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #bfbfbf; padding-left:8pt">Double Trigger for Payment of Separation Benefits under CIC Plan</TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom" STYLE="BORDER-LEFT:1px solid #bfbfbf; BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #bfbfbf">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD VALIGN="top" STYLE="BORDER-RIGHT:1px solid #bfbfbf; BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #bfbfbf; padding-right:8pt">
<P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:2.25em; text-indent:-2.25em; font-size:8pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#4c4c4c">&#149;</FONT>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Consummation of a CIC; and</P>
<P STYLE="font-size:4pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:1pt; margin-left:2.25em; text-indent:-2.25em; font-size:8pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#4c4c4c">&#149;</FONT>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Termination of employment by Mondel&#275;z International
other than for &#147;cause,&#148; or by the NEO for &#147;good reason&#148;. The termination of an NEO&#146;s employment due to death or disability does not trigger CIC Plan benefits.</P></TD></TR>
<TR STYLE="font-family:ARIAL; font-size:8pt">
<TD VALIGN="top" STYLE="BORDER-LEFT:1px solid #bfbfbf; BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #bfbfbf; padding-left:8pt">Definition of &#147;Cause&#148;</TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom" STYLE="BORDER-LEFT:1px solid #bfbfbf; BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #bfbfbf">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD VALIGN="top" STYLE="BORDER-RIGHT:1px solid #bfbfbf; BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #bfbfbf; padding-right:8pt">
<P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:2.25em; text-indent:-2.25em; font-size:8pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#4c4c4c">&#149;</FONT>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Continued failure to substantially perform the
participant&#146;s job duties (other than resulting from incapacity due to disability);</P> <P STYLE="font-size:4pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:2.25em; text-indent:-2.25em; font-size:8pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#4c4c4c">&#149;</FONT>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Gross negligence, dishonesty or violation of any
reasonable rule or regulation of Mondel&#275;z International where the violation results in significant damage to Mondel&#275;z International; or</P> <P STYLE="font-size:4pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:1pt; margin-left:2.25em; text-indent:-2.25em; font-size:8pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#4c4c4c">&#149;</FONT>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Engaging in other conduct which adversely reflects on
Mondel&#275;z International in any material respect.</P></TD></TR>
<TR STYLE="font-family:ARIAL; font-size:8pt">
<TD VALIGN="top" STYLE="BORDER-LEFT:1px solid #bfbfbf; BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #bfbfbf; padding-left:8pt">Definition of &#147;Good Reason&#148;</TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom" STYLE="BORDER-LEFT:1px solid #bfbfbf; BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #bfbfbf">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD VALIGN="top" STYLE="BORDER-RIGHT:1px solid #bfbfbf; BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #bfbfbf; padding-right:8pt"> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:8pt; font-family:ARIAL">We take any other action that results in the following:</P>
<P STYLE="font-size:4pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:2.25em; text-indent:-2.25em; font-size:8pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#4c4c4c">&#149;</FONT>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Material reduction in job duties;</P>
<P STYLE="font-size:4pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:2.25em; text-indent:-2.25em; font-size:8pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#4c4c4c">&#149;</FONT>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Material reduction in compensation;</P>
<P STYLE="font-size:4pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:2.25em; text-indent:-2.25em; font-size:8pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#4c4c4c">&#149;</FONT>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Relocation beyond 50 miles; or</P>
<P STYLE="font-size:4pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:1pt; margin-left:2.25em; text-indent:-2.25em; font-size:8pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#4c4c4c">&#149;</FONT>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Increased business travel.</P></TD></TR>
<TR STYLE="font-family:ARIAL; font-size:8pt">
<TD VALIGN="top" STYLE="BORDER-LEFT:1px solid #bfbfbf; BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #bfbfbf; padding-left:8pt">Severance Amounts</TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom" STYLE="BORDER-LEFT:1px solid #bfbfbf; BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #bfbfbf">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD VALIGN="top" STYLE="BORDER-RIGHT:1px solid #bfbfbf; BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #bfbfbf; padding-right:8pt">
<P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:2.25em; text-indent:-2.25em; font-size:8pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#4c4c4c">&#149;</FONT>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;CEO: three times base salary plus target annual
incentive;</P> <P STYLE="font-size:4pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:2.25em; text-indent:-2.25em; font-size:8pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#4c4c4c">&#149;</FONT>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;All other NEOs: two times base salary plus target annual
incentive;</P> <P STYLE="font-size:4pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:2.25em; text-indent:-2.25em; font-size:8pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#4c4c4c">&#149;</FONT>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Additional credited years of pension service and welfare
benefits equal, in years, to the severance multiple within Section 409A standards;</P> <P STYLE="font-size:4pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:2.25em; text-indent:-2.25em; font-size:8pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#4c4c4c">&#149;</FONT>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Continuation of financial counseling and car allowances
for three years for the CEO and two years for the other NEOs;</P> <P STYLE="font-size:4pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:2.25em; text-indent:-2.25em; font-size:8pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#4c4c4c">&#149;</FONT>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Outplacement services up to two years following the CIC;
and</P> <P STYLE="font-size:4pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:1pt; margin-left:2.25em; text-indent:-2.25em; font-size:8pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#4c4c4c">&#149;</FONT>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;The foregoing benefits are subject to non-compete and
non-solicit restrictive covenants.</P></TD></TR></TABLE>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt ; font-size:8pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="font-size:12pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:9pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="right"><FONT COLOR="#4c4c4c">MONDEL&#274;Z INTERNATIONAL&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;71 </FONT></P>
